1
00:01:52,880 --> 00:01:55,010
What's going on?

2
00:01:55,010 --> 00:01:57,500
The path in the clouds
looks just like an obi.

3
00:02:03,810 --> 00:02:07,310
It doesn't appear
to have formed naturally.

4
00:02:03,810 --> 00:02:07,310
Oh, Nami!

5
00:02:07,310 --> 00:02:09,530
There's no way this is natural!

6
00:02:19,480 --> 00:02:22,300
There's the exit!
Something's written on it!

7
00:02:22,300 --> 00:02:23,660
God Land...

8
00:02:23,660 --> 00:02:26,120
God Land, Skypiea?!

9
00:02:28,290 --> 00:02:29,540
It's not an exit...

10
00:02:29,540 --> 00:02:31,290
it's an entrance!

11
00:02:58,150 --> 00:02:59,400
An island!

12
00:03:00,600 --> 00:03:02,920
It's the sky island!

13
00:03:09,380 --> 00:03:13,250
Hey... that sign... said Skypiea.

14
00:03:13,250 --> 00:03:13,840
Yeah!

15
00:03:13,840 --> 00:03:17,050
The map Luffy found had
that same name written on it.

16
00:03:19,640 --> 00:03:25,190
So the galleon that fell on us
really did come from here.

17
00:03:25,190 --> 00:03:29,430
They witnessed this view
200 long years ago!

18
00:03:37,270 --> 00:03:38,940
What is this place?!

19
00:03:39,190 --> 00:03:41,900
You can totally smell
adventure in the air!

20
00:03:41,900 --> 00:03:43,660
Ah! Wait, you idiot!

21
00:03:44,190 --> 00:03:45,500
You can stand up in it.

22
00:03:47,290 --> 00:03:50,330
Hey! You okay, Usopp?

23
00:03:54,850 --> 00:03:57,760
So this island's made of fluffy clouds?

24
00:03:57,760 --> 00:03:59,500
They're super fluffy, right?

25
00:03:59,500 --> 00:04:01,130
So fluffy!

26
00:04:02,760 --> 00:04:04,890
Let's go to the shore!

27
00:04:06,490 --> 00:04:08,000
The sky island!

28
00:04:08,000 --> 00:04:10,260
Me too! Me too!

29
00:04:10,260 --> 00:04:12,350
I'm gonna go change!

30
00:04:13,130 --> 00:04:15,840
Hey, Luffy! What about the anchor?

31
00:04:15,840 --> 00:04:17,890
There's no sea floor out here, right?

32
00:04:17,890 --> 00:04:20,070
Who cares?

33
00:04:20,820 --> 00:04:22,350
Yeah, who cares?!

34
00:04:22,350 --> 00:04:23,330
Yeah!

35
00:04:23,330 --> 00:04:24,440
Just forget about it!

36
00:04:24,440 --> 00:04:25,270
Forget about it!

37
00:04:25,270 --> 00:04:26,240
Me too! Me too!

38
00:04:29,140 --> 00:04:33,270
Come down already!
This beach is super fluffy!

39
00:04:33,270 --> 00:04:35,460
Roll! Roll! Roll!

40
00:04:35,460 --> 00:04:36,950
Let me do it too!

41
00:04:41,610 --> 00:04:44,880
This view is amazing.

42
00:04:44,880 --> 00:04:46,710
It's like something out of a dream.

43
00:04:46,710 --> 00:04:48,520
Yeah, it sure is.

44
00:04:48,520 --> 00:04:51,340
And look at how they're
getting all carried away.

45
00:04:51,880 --> 00:04:53,890
They're hopeless...

46
00:04:54,270 --> 00:04:56,430
Yahoo!

47
00:04:57,240 --> 00:04:59,190
As if you aren't.

48
00:05:00,110 --> 00:05:02,780
Ow! Ow! Ow! Sorry! I said sorry!

49
00:05:07,300 --> 00:05:10,930
I guess we brought
the south bird with us, huh?

50
00:05:10,930 --> 00:05:12,920
We forgot to let him go.

51
00:05:12,920 --> 00:05:17,120
It looks like people are living here,
so he'll likely get by without our help.

52
00:05:17,120 --> 00:05:19,470
If he really tries,
he could even get back down.

53
00:05:19,470 --> 00:05:20,760
He's a bird, after all.

54
00:05:22,200 --> 00:05:24,510
Oh, hey, what about the anchor?

55
00:05:25,060 --> 00:05:26,680
It hit bottom.

56
00:05:26,680 --> 00:05:29,720
Looks like those fluffy clouds
are the base of this island.

57
00:05:29,720 --> 00:05:33,220
That means that the island
is floating on this sea.

58
00:05:33,220 --> 00:05:37,190
I wonder if an island can remain
in the same spot without drifting away.

59
00:05:37,190 --> 00:05:40,650
Well, all we can do
is take things as they come.

60
00:05:40,650 --> 00:05:43,730
Actually, all of this is hard to believe.

61
00:05:43,730 --> 00:05:47,110
The only thing we know for sure
is that this sky island exists.

62
00:05:51,910 --> 00:05:53,070
See?!

63
00:05:54,130 --> 00:05:58,210
There's no denying what's
right in front of me.

64
00:05:58,210 --> 00:05:59,580
Get down here!

65
00:05:59,580 --> 00:06:01,990
You can't drown when
it's this shallow, right?!

66
00:06:03,930 --> 00:06:05,130
What about you?

67
00:06:06,600 --> 00:06:08,260
Yeah, I'll go too.

68
00:06:11,050 --> 00:06:13,310
The smell of adventure, huh?

69
00:06:14,930 --> 00:06:17,770
I've never thought of
sailing or going ashore...

70
00:06:19,020 --> 00:06:20,730
as an adventure.

71
00:06:26,730 --> 00:06:31,340
For some reason, this sky island
is making me sleepy...

72
00:06:35,130 --> 00:06:37,110
Hello, this is your captain speaking.

73
00:06:37,110 --> 00:06:40,710
I'm having too much fun to figure out
what we should do first, over.

74
00:06:40,710 --> 00:06:45,460
This is Usopp. Why don't we
take it easy for a bit, over.

75
00:06:45,810 --> 00:06:47,970
Take it easy? Sounds good!

76
00:06:47,970 --> 00:06:48,930
Denied!

77
00:06:48,930 --> 00:06:51,260
What?! "Denied" means no, you know!

78
00:06:51,260 --> 00:06:52,450
Look here...

79
00:06:52,450 --> 00:06:55,010
Mysterious flowers are in bloom.

80
00:06:58,530 --> 00:07:00,330
I wonder if they're also balloons.

81
00:07:00,330 --> 00:07:02,400
Do they pop like that fish did?

82
00:07:07,410 --> 00:07:09,080
This is so nice.

83
00:07:09,080 --> 00:07:13,500
The Marines won't be chasing us here,
so we can relax and enjoy ourselves!

84
00:07:16,680 --> 00:07:19,410
Hey, Chopper, look.
What could that be?

85
00:07:21,050 --> 00:07:21,750
Huh?

86
00:07:21,750 --> 00:07:24,020
Ah! I found a strange fruit!

87
00:07:24,020 --> 00:07:26,710
I'm gonna try it!

88
00:07:27,700 --> 00:07:29,640
What the...?

89
00:07:29,640 --> 00:07:31,400
This thing's hard!

90
00:07:32,290 --> 00:07:34,890
Hey, Usopp! I've got
a fruit for you. Here!

91
00:07:36,600 --> 00:07:39,500
Hey, that hurt! Okay, stay right there!

92
00:07:40,980 --> 00:07:42,850
Ahh! Robin my love!

93
00:07:43,510 --> 00:07:46,760
These are sky island flowers.
One for Robin my love...

94
00:07:46,760 --> 00:07:48,470
and one for...

95
00:07:49,170 --> 00:07:50,930
Nami my sweet!

96
00:07:50,930 --> 00:07:54,620
Nami my sweet! A flower for you!

97
00:07:55,590 --> 00:07:58,490
Whoa! This chair is
made of clouds, too!

98
00:07:58,490 --> 00:08:01,380
There must be some technology
to make items from clouds.

99
00:08:01,380 --> 00:08:03,690
But it's different
from the fluffy clouds.

100
00:08:03,690 --> 00:08:05,150
It's puffy.

101
00:08:03,690 --> 00:08:06,630
Nami! A flower for you!

102
00:08:06,630 --> 00:08:09,590
But why am I getting wet
if this is just a sea of clouds?

103
00:08:09,590 --> 00:08:11,550
Hm? Oh, good timing.

104
00:08:18,350 --> 00:08:19,500
Sorry!

105
00:08:21,060 --> 00:08:24,100
Huh? What the hell is this? A fox?

106
00:08:26,790 --> 00:08:29,190
Hmm? What's that sound?

107
00:08:31,780 --> 00:08:34,700
Hey. Who is that person? Up there!

108
00:08:35,450 --> 00:08:37,780
Did that guerrilla return?!

109
00:08:37,780 --> 00:08:41,040
Whistle! Where's the whistle?!
Let's ask that guy to save us again!

110
00:08:41,040 --> 00:08:44,790
No, hold on. That's not
a guerrilla. That's...

111
00:08:45,140 --> 00:08:46,630
an angel...

112
00:08:48,000 --> 00:08:49,300
An angel?

113
00:08:54,750 --> 00:08:56,050
Heso!

114
00:08:57,000 --> 00:08:58,100
– Heso!
– Heso?

115
00:08:58,100 --> 00:08:59,760
Suu, come here.

116
00:09:02,330 --> 00:09:04,100
Did you come from the Blue Sea?

117
00:09:04,100 --> 00:09:06,260
Yeah, we flew up here from below.

118
00:09:06,260 --> 00:09:08,340
Do you live here?

119
00:09:08,340 --> 00:09:10,360
Yes, I'm a resident here.

120
00:09:12,690 --> 00:09:15,350
Welcome to Skypiea's Angel Beach!

121
00:09:16,280 --> 00:09:18,070
Would you like to drink that?

122
00:09:18,070 --> 00:09:20,200
Hm? Yeah...

123
00:09:21,320 --> 00:09:25,840
A conash's shell is as hard as iron,
so you can't bite it.

124
00:09:25,840 --> 00:09:27,820
You cut it at the bottom.

125
00:09:31,250 --> 00:09:32,680
Here you go!

126
00:09:36,490 --> 00:09:38,850
Yum!

127
00:09:38,850 --> 00:09:40,470
What?! It's that good?!

128
00:09:40,470 --> 00:09:41,950
Let me try it, too!

129
00:09:42,740 --> 00:09:45,830
Yum!

130
00:09:45,830 --> 00:09:47,400
My name is Conis.

131
00:09:47,400 --> 00:09:50,110
This is Suu, a cloud fox.

132
00:09:50,110 --> 00:09:52,940
If I can be of any help at all,
please let me know.

133
00:09:52,940 --> 00:09:54,920
Well, you see...

134
00:09:54,920 --> 00:09:56,660
your gaze is setting my heart ablaze–

135
00:09:56,660 --> 00:09:59,100
Ow!

136
00:09:58,060 --> 00:09:59,100
Move it!

137
00:09:59,860 --> 00:10:02,090
There's so much we'd like to know.

138
00:10:02,090 --> 00:10:05,790
To us, this place is full of mysteries.

139
00:10:06,120 --> 00:10:08,370
Okay. Please ask me anything.

140
00:10:08,370 --> 00:10:10,920
Hey, something's coming.

141
00:10:10,920 --> 00:10:12,500
Oh, that's my father.

142
00:10:12,500 --> 00:10:14,720
Heso, Conis!

143
00:10:14,720 --> 00:10:17,080
Yes, heso, Father!

144
00:10:17,080 --> 00:10:19,340
Hey, what are you guys saying?

145
00:10:19,340 --> 00:10:22,970
Hm? What's that thing he's riding on?

146
00:10:22,970 --> 00:10:25,220
Oh, are you talking about the waver?

147
00:10:25,220 --> 00:10:27,980
Wow! That thing is so cool!

148
00:10:28,740 --> 00:10:30,060
Waver...

149
00:10:30,390 --> 00:10:33,820
I'm sorry, I'm coming to a stop!

150
00:10:40,790 --> 00:10:43,740
Is everyone all right?

151
00:10:43,740 --> 00:10:45,700
You're the one who crashed!

152
00:10:46,060 --> 00:10:49,950
Hey, Luffy. Didn't you salvage
something similar from the seabed before?

153
00:10:49,950 --> 00:10:51,380
Yeah, I did, didn't I?

154
00:10:53,140 --> 00:10:55,340
I read about it in Noland's diary—

155
00:10:55,810 --> 00:10:58,030
a boat that can be
propelled without wind!

156
00:10:58,980 --> 00:11:01,340
Are they your friends, Conis?

157
00:11:01,690 --> 00:11:03,820
Yes. We've just become acquainted.

158
00:11:03,820 --> 00:11:05,490
They're from the Blue Sea.

159
00:11:05,490 --> 00:11:09,310
I see. Then there must be many things
that you're wondering about.

160
00:11:09,310 --> 00:11:11,400
This is the White-White Sea. I'm sorry.

161
00:11:11,400 --> 00:11:12,980
Oh, no need to apologize.

162
00:11:12,980 --> 00:11:16,810
Pardon my late introduction,
but my name is Pagaya. I'm sorry.

163
00:11:16,810 --> 00:11:18,570
Oh, no, no, no. We're sorry.

164
00:11:18,960 --> 00:11:21,350
Father, were you able
to catch some fish?

165
00:11:21,350 --> 00:11:23,320
Yes, I had a large haul.

166
00:11:23,710 --> 00:11:27,060
Oh, yes, why don't you
all come to our house?

167
00:11:27,060 --> 00:11:29,330
I'll make a meal for you
with the sky food.

168
00:11:29,330 --> 00:11:31,570
Are you sure?!
Then let's go! Let's go!

169
00:11:31,570 --> 00:11:33,290
Sky island cuisine?!

170
00:11:33,290 --> 00:11:35,960
Let me help you!

171
00:11:36,650 --> 00:11:38,800
Before we go,
can I ask you a question?

172
00:11:38,800 --> 00:11:43,180
This boat doesn't have a sail,
and you weren't paddling, either.

173
00:11:43,690 --> 00:11:45,850
How did you propel it on the sea?

174
00:11:46,470 --> 00:11:49,720
Oh, so you're not familiar with dials?

175
00:11:49,720 --> 00:11:51,310
Hm? Dials?

176
00:11:57,220 --> 00:12:00,690
Wh-What is this shaking?!
I can't stop it!

177
00:12:03,880 --> 00:12:06,360
Oh, no! Is he all right?!

178
00:12:06,360 --> 00:12:09,960
Heavens! I let him use
the waver. I'm sorry!

179
00:12:10,600 --> 00:12:13,880
On that note, I wonder how
this sea treats those with powers.

180
00:12:13,880 --> 00:12:17,030
Oh, yeah. This isn't an ordinary sea,

181
00:12:17,030 --> 00:12:19,380
so he may just float.

182
00:12:22,490 --> 00:12:23,200
He sank.

183
00:12:23,200 --> 00:12:24,660
So he doesn't float.

184
00:12:24,660 --> 00:12:27,300
Ahh! He's in danger!

185
00:12:27,300 --> 00:12:31,270
That was close! He was just about
to go through the clouds!

186
00:12:31,270 --> 00:12:34,770
We had a late start
because of your nonsense!

187
00:12:34,770 --> 00:12:37,610
Did you really have to jump in too?

188
00:12:37,610 --> 00:12:39,940
Sky island scary, sky island scary...

189
00:12:40,440 --> 00:12:43,750
I let a beginner use my
watercraft. I'm sorry.

190
00:12:43,750 --> 00:12:49,320
Wavers are so light that their rudders are
easily taken over even by small waves.

191
00:12:49,320 --> 00:12:53,540
Unless you know the sea well,
you'll have difficulty handling it. I'm sorry.

192
00:12:54,080 --> 00:12:56,790
I've only recently
learned how to ride it.

193
00:12:56,790 --> 00:12:58,930
It's that hard?

194
00:12:58,930 --> 00:13:01,750
Well, with training, you can
ride it in about ten years.

195
00:13:01,750 --> 00:13:03,300
That's a lot of training!

196
00:13:03,710 --> 00:13:05,300
Hey, she's riding it!

197
00:13:05,300 --> 00:13:06,510
This is awesome!

198
00:13:06,510 --> 00:13:10,030
Nami! You're the coolest!

199
00:13:10,030 --> 00:13:13,030
Whoa! This is incredible!
I can't believe it!

200
00:13:13,030 --> 00:13:15,350
How is she able to ride that thing?!

201
00:13:15,350 --> 00:13:17,690
It definitely requires
some getting used to!

202
00:13:18,070 --> 00:13:21,400
This is too delicate
for you to handle, Luffy!

203
00:13:22,990 --> 00:13:24,240
Hey, Nami!

204
00:13:24,240 --> 00:13:26,850
Get off so you can come
with us to the old guy's house!

205
00:13:26,850 --> 00:13:27,990
You stupid head!

206
00:13:27,990 --> 00:13:29,360
Give it up!

207
00:13:29,360 --> 00:13:31,940
You stupid head!

208
00:13:30,600 --> 00:13:31,940
You guys go on ahead!

209
00:13:31,940 --> 00:13:34,760
Mister! Can I stay out here
a little longer and have fun?

210
00:13:34,760 --> 00:13:36,960
That's fine! Be careful!

211
00:13:37,670 --> 00:13:42,100
It's like a dream! I'm sailing a boat so easily
without a care for the wind's direction!

212
00:13:42,100 --> 00:13:45,380
I wonder if we can use it
on the regular sea.

213
00:13:45,880 --> 00:13:49,020
Hey! Is that a construction site?

214
00:13:51,280 --> 00:13:53,600
Oh, that's a cloud quarry.

215
00:13:54,620 --> 00:13:57,960
It's a site where they mine clouds
for other applications.

216
00:13:57,960 --> 00:14:00,560
You can mine clouds?

217
00:14:00,560 --> 00:14:04,660
You took a milky road to get
to the White-White Sea, right?

218
00:14:04,660 --> 00:14:08,250
Milky road? Oh, you mean
that winding sea path?

219
00:14:08,250 --> 00:14:10,780
That's an artificial canal.

220
00:14:10,800 --> 00:14:13,540
It's made out of island clouds
taken from here.

221
00:14:13,960 --> 00:14:16,820
There are two kinds of natural clouds.

222
00:14:16,820 --> 00:14:19,950
The ones your ship traveled on
are called sea clouds,

223
00:14:19,950 --> 00:14:25,550
and the floating ones that you can
walk on are called island clouds.

224
00:14:26,260 --> 00:14:29,170
Either way, they're
not ordinary clouds.

225
00:14:29,170 --> 00:14:33,800
Right. Their condensation nucleus
is different from other clouds.

226
00:14:34,440 --> 00:14:38,670
I've heard that a mineral called
seastone exists in the Blue Sea.

227
00:14:38,670 --> 00:14:41,730
Seastone? Is there
a connection to these clouds?

228
00:14:41,730 --> 00:14:42,520
Yes.

229
00:14:42,520 --> 00:14:46,670
When the stone's corneous particles,
known as pyrobroin,

230
00:14:46,670 --> 00:14:50,380
are carried into the sky by volcanoes,
they gain moisture.

231
00:14:50,380 --> 00:14:55,450
Then, sea and island clouds form
depending on the moisture's density.

232
00:14:55,970 --> 00:14:58,120
Oh, I see. That particle.

233
00:14:58,120 --> 00:15:01,410
Oh, yeah, that one.

234
00:15:01,410 --> 00:15:04,440
We used to play with them a lot
as kids... corneous particles...

235
00:15:04,440 --> 00:15:06,130
Cut the crap!

236
00:15:06,440 --> 00:15:08,960
Well, anyway, there are
three cloud types here.

237
00:15:08,960 --> 00:15:11,170
Sea and island clouds,
which are natural,

238
00:15:11,170 --> 00:15:15,640
and man-made ones that are
processed from island clouds.

239
00:15:16,050 --> 00:15:18,000
Now, this way, please.

240
00:15:18,000 --> 00:15:20,340
What a great view!

241
00:15:20,340 --> 00:15:23,310
Oh! We can see Nami
riding the waver, too!

242
00:15:23,310 --> 00:15:25,820
Hey, Luffy, what are you doing?

243
00:15:25,820 --> 00:15:29,750
Why can she ride it so easily?

244
00:15:29,750 --> 00:15:30,390
Sink!

245
00:15:30,390 --> 00:15:31,490
Grow up!

246
00:15:32,150 --> 00:15:34,920
Ouch! You made me
bite my tonuge, Sanji!

247
00:15:34,920 --> 00:15:37,340
Hey, mister! Where's the kitchen?

248
00:15:37,340 --> 00:15:39,870
Come! It's right this way!

249
00:15:44,730 --> 00:15:45,880
What's wrong?

250
00:15:47,430 --> 00:15:51,420
Well, I've never seen this before,
so I had a little taste,

251
00:15:51,420 --> 00:15:56,960
but, how should I say it,
this blue sauce's flavor was intense.

252
00:15:56,960 --> 00:15:58,300
It made my tongue numb.

253
00:15:58,300 --> 00:15:58,950
Oh...

254
00:16:00,410 --> 00:16:02,040
That one's spoiled. I'm sorry.

255
00:16:02,040 --> 00:16:04,610
Hey, don't keep stuff like this around!

256
00:16:04,610 --> 00:16:07,740
I tried it without thinking it'd be spoiled!

257
00:16:05,610 --> 00:16:07,730
It sounds like they're having fun.

258
00:16:07,730 --> 00:16:11,180
You knew it was going bad, right?!

259
00:16:07,740 --> 00:16:11,180
He's probably excited about
all the new sky food.

260
00:16:12,690 --> 00:16:14,410
Miss, I don't mean to be abrupt, but...

261
00:16:15,240 --> 00:16:18,820
would you tell us more about
the dials you mentioned earlier?

262
00:16:18,820 --> 00:16:23,420
Sure. Well... how should I explain it?

263
00:16:25,540 --> 00:16:29,300
Ah... This is a puffy chair.

264
00:16:29,300 --> 00:16:32,970
Hm? What? It's a seashell.

265
00:16:32,970 --> 00:16:36,930
Yes. Please say something to it.

266
00:16:36,930 --> 00:16:39,560
Usopp is stupid!

267
00:16:38,590 --> 00:16:39,560
Hey! Why?

268
00:16:39,560 --> 00:16:40,560
Why? Why me?

269
00:16:42,340 --> 00:16:45,190
Now, please press
the apex of that shell.

270
00:16:46,050 --> 00:16:47,480
What's an apex?

271
00:16:47,490 --> 00:16:49,410
It's the tip of the shell.

272
00:16:49,410 --> 00:16:51,110
Usopp is stupid!

273
00:16:51,110 --> 00:16:53,480
Hey! Why? Why? Why me?

274
00:16:51,110 --> 00:16:53,900
Ahh! The seashell made fun of Usopp!

275
00:16:53,900 --> 00:16:55,720
No, that's your voice!

276
00:16:54,680 --> 00:16:57,070
Now, please press
the apex of that shell.

277
00:16:57,470 --> 00:17:01,360
Whoa! That's amazing!
It stored the sounds?

278
00:17:01,360 --> 00:17:03,040
So that seashell is a dial?

279
00:17:03,040 --> 00:17:06,130
Yes. This is called a tone dial.

280
00:17:06,130 --> 00:17:11,210
It's a seashell from the White-White Sea
that records and replays sounds.

281
00:17:11,210 --> 00:17:14,560
But the sea here is bottomless, right?

282
00:17:14,560 --> 00:17:16,920
Where do they live?

283
00:17:16,920 --> 00:17:18,930
They live in the reefs of the shallows.

284
00:17:19,390 --> 00:17:22,940
But an object like that shouldn't
be able to move a waver.

285
00:17:23,460 --> 00:17:26,420
You're right. This is the kind
that powers the wavers.

286
00:17:26,420 --> 00:17:28,480
This is a small one,

287
00:17:28,480 --> 00:17:31,110
but it's fundamentally
the same as the tone dials.

288
00:17:35,850 --> 00:17:37,940
So, wind comes out of this one.

289
00:17:37,940 --> 00:17:39,280
Let me try it.

290
00:17:40,150 --> 00:17:41,950
This is called a breath dial.

291
00:17:41,950 --> 00:17:45,450
You can store wind
and release it at any time.

292
00:17:49,320 --> 00:17:52,300
The capacity varies depending
on the size of the shell,

293
00:17:52,300 --> 00:17:56,070
but by attaching this to the stern,
you can move a light boat.

294
00:17:56,610 --> 00:17:58,390
That's the waver.

295
00:17:59,190 --> 00:18:03,810
I see. So, it moved by blowing wind.

296
00:18:03,810 --> 00:18:05,560
I wanna ride a waver.

297
00:18:06,840 --> 00:18:11,690
There are actually other kinds,
like a skating type or board type,

298
00:18:11,690 --> 00:18:14,570
although riding the waver
is as much as I can handle.

299
00:18:15,100 --> 00:18:16,610
I wanna ride it.

300
00:18:16,610 --> 00:18:18,040
I'm jealous of Nami.

301
00:18:18,040 --> 00:18:20,810
Too bad we can't use
the one we have.

302
00:18:20,810 --> 00:18:22,740
You have a waver?

303
00:18:22,740 --> 00:18:27,080
Yeah, we came across one
that was all beat up.

304
00:18:27,080 --> 00:18:30,970
But for starters, it's 200 years old.
There's no way it works.

305
00:18:30,970 --> 00:18:33,000
We can't know that for sure.

306
00:18:33,680 --> 00:18:36,810
Dials were always made
with the remains of dead shellfish,

307
00:18:36,810 --> 00:18:40,900
so they'll work practically forever
unless the shell itself is damaged.

308
00:18:40,900 --> 00:18:41,930
See?!

309
00:18:41,930 --> 00:18:43,370
But you can't steer it, right?

310
00:18:43,370 --> 00:18:45,050
I'm jealous...

311
00:18:45,050 --> 00:18:47,670
Sounds like other kinds
of dials exist as well, huh?

312
00:18:47,670 --> 00:18:48,730
Is this one, too?

313
00:18:48,730 --> 00:18:51,190
Yes. It's a lamp dial.

314
00:18:52,060 --> 00:18:54,270
Whoa! The seashell lit up!

315
00:18:55,030 --> 00:18:58,240
Dials are varied. For instance,
flame dials hold fire;

316
00:18:58,840 --> 00:19:01,200
flavor dials, scents;

317
00:19:01,200 --> 00:19:04,540
and vision dials, moving pictures.

318
00:19:05,160 --> 00:19:09,180
How interesting! How interesting!

319
00:19:09,180 --> 00:19:13,030
To people in the sky,
they're indispensable.

320
00:19:13,030 --> 00:19:13,840
I see.

321
00:19:13,840 --> 00:19:16,280
So, you could say that...

322
00:19:17,880 --> 00:19:20,600
sky culture goes hand in hand
with dial energy.

323
00:19:30,440 --> 00:19:32,520
Now, the food is ready!

324
00:19:32,520 --> 00:19:36,900
It's a hearty sky seafood course
with sky island fruits!

325
00:19:36,900 --> 00:19:38,080
Wow!

326
00:19:38,080 --> 00:19:39,610
Amazing!

327
00:19:42,700 --> 00:19:44,640
Yum!

328
00:19:44,640 --> 00:19:47,660
This lobster...! How can
I put its taste into words?!

329
00:19:53,430 --> 00:19:55,920
Hey, where did Nami go?

330
00:19:56,450 --> 00:19:58,150
She's out there on the sea, isn't she?

331
00:19:58,150 --> 00:19:59,270
No, she isn't.

332
00:19:59,270 --> 00:20:02,470
Then she probably went farther out.
Don't worry about her.

333
00:20:04,810 --> 00:20:07,380
Father, I wonder if she's all right.

334
00:20:07,380 --> 00:20:10,980
So do I, Conis. It's a bit concerning.

335
00:20:11,700 --> 00:20:12,980
Why? What's the matter?

336
00:20:13,880 --> 00:20:15,060
Here in Skypiea,

337
00:20:15,060 --> 00:20:19,530
there's a place that we're forbidden
from entering, no matter what.

338
00:20:20,760 --> 00:20:23,400
That place is next to this island.

339
00:20:23,400 --> 00:20:26,650
So if you travel a bit by waver,
you can get there.

340
00:20:30,040 --> 00:20:31,510
It's huge...

341
00:20:32,130 --> 00:20:33,580
What is this?

342
00:20:33,580 --> 00:20:37,390
Forbidden from entering?

343
00:20:37,390 --> 00:20:38,590
Why's that?

344
00:20:39,770 --> 00:20:41,050
It's sacred ground.

345
00:20:41,050 --> 00:20:42,270
Sacred ground?

346
00:20:43,090 --> 00:20:45,050
We call that place...

347
00:20:47,000 --> 00:20:50,020
Upper Yard, the land
in which our god lives.

348
00:02:59,490 --> 00:03:04,370
God Land, Skypiea
White-White Sea

349
00:02:59,490 --> 00:03:04,370
God Land, Skypiea
White-White Sea

350
00:09:40,600 --> 00:09:49,810
Conis & Cloud Fox Suu
Angel Beach, Skypiea Residents

351
